-- Populate ideal_answer JSONB for 15 depth questions

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "End-to-end RL training pipeline for query generation using a 3B parameter model with composite reward signal and PPO/GRPO optimization.", "outline": ["Architecture: LoRA fine-tuning Llama 3.2 3B for query generation from item attributes", "Reward signal: composite of retrieval recall (40%), LLM diversity judge (30%), and relevance judge (30%)", "Training: PPO with KL penalty vs GRPO with group statistics baseline — GRPO won on memory efficiency", "Infrastructure: vLLM optimized from 1 to 10 inferences/sec, custom SQLite cache for billions of pairwise predictions", "Iteration: RL training loop with periodic human evaluation samples to detect reward hacking"], "full_response": "The RL training pipeline starts with a 3B parameter Llama 3.2 model that we fine-tune using LoRA to generate shopping intent queries from item attributes. The input is a structured representation of an item (title, category, brand, price, key attributes), and the output is a set of natural language queries that describe what a customer shopping for complementary items might search for.\n\nThe reward signal is composite, which was a deliberate design choice to prevent reward hacking. It combines three components: retrieval recall at 40% weight (do the generated queries actually retrieve relevant complementary items from our FAISS index?), LLM diversity judge at 30% (are the retrieved items genuinely diverse and complementary, not just similar?), and relevance judge at 30% (are the retrieved items relevant to the anchor item''s use case?). The diversity and relevance scores come from an LLM-as-judge framework with rubrics I developed specifically for complementary recommendations.\n\nFor optimization, I implemented both PPO and GRPO and compared them. PPO uses a learned critic network to estimate the value baseline, with clipped surrogate objectives to prevent large policy updates. GRPO (Group Relative Policy Optimization) eliminates the critic entirely — instead, it samples a group of outputs for each input and uses the group''s mean reward as the baseline. GRPO won in our setting because it saved significant GPU memory (no critic network to maintain) while achieving comparable policy quality. The tradeoff is that GRPO needs larger batch sizes to get stable baseline estimates, but we had the compute budget for that.\n\nThe infrastructure was a major engineering effort. I optimized vLLM for inference throughput, taking it from about 1 inference per second to 10 through KV cache tuning, batch size optimization, and tensor parallelism across 8 GPUs. For the reward computation loop, I built a custom SQLite caching layer that scales to billions of pairwise predictions — when the reward function evaluates a (query, retrieved_item) pair, it first checks the cache. This cache data became reusable for supervised fine-tuning on other models across the team.\n\nThe training loop runs for multiple epochs with periodic checkpointing. After each epoch, I run a human evaluation sample — 200 randomly selected outputs scored by me for quality — to detect reward hacking (the model finding ways to game the composite reward without actually improving generation quality). The KL penalty term in the loss prevents the policy from diverging too far from the initial supervised fine-tuned model."}'::jsonb WHERE id = '5bbdbd36-0872-4e86-8e67-0b3eacfa69ff';

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "Composite reward design with retrieval metrics and LLM judge to prevent reward hacking in query generation RL.", "outline": ["Dual reward prevents gaming: retrieval recall alone led to generic high-recall queries, LLM judge alone led to verbose descriptions", "Weights (40/30/30) tuned empirically by correlating reward components with human quality judgments", "Reward hacking mitigations: dual reward, human eval samples every epoch, KL penalty from SFT checkpoint", "LLM judge bias detection: backtested against 2 known-failed launches to confirm judge catches real degradation"], "full_response": "The reward signal design was the most critical engineering decision in the RL pipeline. I chose a composite reward because single-objective rewards consistently led to degenerate behavior.\n\nWhen I trained with retrieval recall alone, the model learned to generate very broad, generic queries that retrieved many items — high recall but terrible precision. The queries were things like ''popular electronics'' instead of specific complementary intents like ''gaming mouse for mechanical keyboard setup.'' When I trained with the LLM diversity judge alone, the model generated verbose, descriptive text that scored well on the judge''s rubric but produced poor retrieval results because the text didn''t match how our search index was built.\n\nThe composite weights (40% retrieval recall, 30% LLM diversity, 30% relevance) were tuned empirically. I generated 500 outputs from the SFT checkpoint, had each scored by all three reward components, and also scored them myself on a 1-5 quality scale. I then ran a regression to find the weighting that best predicted my human quality judgments. The 40/30/30 split had the highest correlation (r=0.82) with human scores.\n\nReward hacking mitigation operates at three levels. First, the dual reward itself — gaming one component typically hurts another, creating natural tension. Second, I run human evaluation samples every training epoch. I take 200 random outputs and score them manually. If human quality flatlines or drops while the reward metric keeps climbing, that''s reward hacking — the model found an exploit in the reward function. Third, the KL penalty from the SFT checkpoint prevents the policy from diverging too far into unexplored territory where the reward signal is unreliable.\n\nFor the LLM judge specifically, I backtested it against two launches we knew had failed in A/B testing. The judge correctly identified the quality degradation in both cases — one where query diversity dropped (the intent-based index cannibalization issue) and one where retrieval relevance degraded for international markets. This gave me confidence the judge was measuring something real, not just pattern-matching on surface features."}'::jsonb WHERE id = 'a33bf87d-8097-4161-b268-68ffe4eeb2b8';

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "GRPO eliminates the critic network using group statistics as baseline, winning on memory efficiency vs PPO for our 3B model training.", "outline": ["PPO: critic network estimates value baseline, clipped surrogate objective, stable but memory-heavy", "GRPO: no critic, samples G outputs per input, uses group mean reward as baseline — saves ~40% GPU memory", "GRPO needs larger batch sizes for stable baselines but our compute budget supported this", "PPO preferred when: small batch sizes, highly variable rewards, need fine-grained credit assignment"], "full_response": "PPO (Proximal Policy Optimization) and GRPO (Group Relative Policy Optimization) are both policy gradient methods for RL fine-tuning, but they differ fundamentally in how they estimate the baseline for variance reduction.\n\nPPO maintains a separate critic network (often the same architecture as the policy but with a value head) that learns to predict the expected reward for a given state. The policy gradient is computed relative to this learned baseline: advantage = reward - V(state). PPO also uses a clipped surrogate objective — it clips the probability ratio between new and old policies to prevent destructively large updates. This makes training stable but requires maintaining and training two networks: the policy and the critic. For a 3B parameter model, the critic roughly doubles GPU memory requirements.\n\nGRPO takes a different approach. For each input, it samples G outputs (we used G=8) from the current policy and computes the reward for each. The baseline is simply the mean reward across the group. The advantage for each output is reward_i minus the group mean. This eliminates the critic entirely — no extra parameters, no extra forward passes for value estimation. The intuition is that within a group of outputs for the same input, relative reward differences are informative about which generations are better.\n\nIn our setting, GRPO won for several reasons. First, memory: dropping the critic saved approximately 40% of GPU memory, which let us use larger batch sizes on the same hardware. Second, simplicity: no need to tune critic learning rate, critic architecture, or the balance between policy and value loss. Third, the group baseline was surprisingly stable because our reward function had moderate variance within groups.\n\nThe tradeoff is that GRPO needs enough samples per group (G >= 4) to get a stable baseline estimate. With G=2, the baseline is just the average of two rewards, which is noisy. We used G=8, which means 8x the generation cost per training step — but since we had already optimized vLLM throughput to 10 inferences/sec, this was feasible.\n\nI would choose PPO over GRPO when: batch sizes must be small (limited compute), reward variance is very high (critic can learn patterns the group mean misses), or you need fine-grained temporal credit assignment (critic can assign value to intermediate states, not just final reward)."}'::jsonb WHERE id = '7beab544-5533-483c-895d-8f4a7bf9a3ab';

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "Three-layer reward hacking prevention: composite dual reward, periodic human evaluation, and KL penalty from SFT checkpoint.", "outline": ["Dual reward creates natural tension — gaming recall hurts diversity and vice versa", "Human eval samples (200/epoch) detect quality divergence from reward metric", "KL penalty constrains policy drift from SFT checkpoint into unreliable reward regions", "Judge bias detection via backtesting against known-failed launches"], "full_response": "Reward hacking is the most dangerous failure mode in RL for language models — the model finds ways to maximize the reward metric without actually improving the quality we care about. I built three layers of defense.\n\nFirst, the composite dual reward creates natural tension between objectives. If the model tries to game retrieval recall by generating overly broad queries, the diversity judge penalizes it. If it tries to game the diversity judge with verbose descriptions, retrieval recall drops because the text doesn''t match the search index. This doesn''t eliminate hacking — a sufficiently powerful model could find a joint exploit — but it raises the bar significantly compared to a single reward.\n\nSecond, periodic human evaluation. Every training epoch, I sample 200 random outputs and score them myself on a 1-5 quality scale. I plot the trend of human quality alongside the RL reward metric. In a healthy training run, both should increase together. If the reward keeps climbing but human quality flatlines or drops, the model has found an exploit. This happened once during development — the model learned to repeat the anchor item''s brand name in every query, which slightly gamed the relevance judge (brand overlap = relevant) without actually generating useful complementary queries. I caught it at epoch 4, diagnosed the exploit, and added brand-name repetition as a negative signal in the relevance rubric.\n\nThird, the KL penalty. The loss function includes a term that penalizes the KL divergence between the RL policy and the original SFT model: L = -reward + beta * KL(pi_RL || pi_SFT). This prevents the policy from wandering too far into regions of generation space where the reward function hasn''t been validated. The beta coefficient controls the tradeoff — higher beta means more conservative exploration. I tuned beta by monitoring the KL divergence during training and setting it high enough that the policy stayed within 2-3 nats of the SFT model.\n\nFor the LLM judge component specifically, I detect bias by backtesting. I take outputs from two launches we know failed in production A/B tests and verify that the judge scores them lower than the successful versions. If the judge can''t distinguish between known-good and known-bad outputs, its reward signal is unreliable and needs recalibration."}'::jsonb WHERE id = 'ea741880-fad1-4c51-baa0-f60c5bd1d4e0';

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "LLM-as-judge evaluation framework with 6 rubrics per carousel type, validated against engagement data and backtested against failed launches.", "outline": ["6 distinct rubrics covering complementary, similar, intent-based, and trending carousel types", "Each rubric scores relevance, diversity, novelty, and category-specific dimensions on 1-5 scale", "Validation: score distributions monotonically predict engagement metrics (CTR, add-to-cart)", "Backtested against 2 known-failed launches — judge correctly identified both degradations"], "full_response": "The LLM-as-judge framework was built to solve a fundamental evaluation gap: we had no systematic way to measure recommendation quality offline before committing to expensive A/B tests. Human evaluation at scale was too slow and expensive, and proxy metrics like embedding similarity didn''t capture what actually mattered to customers.\n\nThe framework has 6 rubrics, one per carousel type (complementary items, similar items, intent-based, trending, recently viewed, and seasonal). Each rubric is a structured prompt that asks the judge to evaluate a set of recommendations along dimensions specific to that carousel type. For complementary items, the dimensions are: cross-category diversity (are items from different but related categories?), use-case coherence (do they serve a common shopping intent?), price-range appropriateness (are complementary items in a reasonable price range relative to the anchor?), and redundancy (are items distinct from each other?). Each dimension gets a 1-5 score with detailed criteria for each level.\n\nThe judge processes (anchor item, list of recommended items) tuples and returns structured JSON with per-dimension scores, an overall quality score, and free-text reasoning. We run this on batches of 10K-50K recommendations sampled from production.\n\nValidation was critical — an LLM judge is only useful if its scores predict real-world outcomes. I validated by computing judge scores for recommendations served in historical A/B tests where we had engagement data. The key finding: judge scores monotonically predicted engagement metrics. Recommendations scored 4-5 by the judge had 2-3x higher click-through rates than those scored 1-2. The correlation wasn''t perfect (the judge can''t predict user-specific preferences), but the ordering was consistent and reliable.\n\nThe strongest validation was backtesting against two launches we knew failed. One was the intent-based index that cannibalized complementary items — the judge correctly scored it lower on diversity. The other was an international market expansion where the model hadn''t been adapted — the judge correctly scored it lower on relevance. If the judge had missed either of these, I wouldn''t have trusted it for production decisions.\n\nThe framework''s most impactful use was blocking the intent-based index launch in international markets (the Insist on Highest Standards story) — the judge quantified the cannibalization that PMs couldn''t see from top-line metrics alone."}'::jsonb WHERE id = '715e44ac-1ac2-4dad-b6f9-160848dcf3f8';

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "LLM judge calibration via engagement correlation, Cohen''s kappa for judge-human agreement, and systematic bias detection through backtesting.", "outline": ["Calibration: judge scores monotonically predict engagement (CTR, add-to-cart) — verified on held-out A/B test data", "Cohen''s kappa between judge and human evaluators: 0.65-0.75 (substantial agreement)", "Disagreement analysis: judge overweights textual similarity, humans weight visual/brand signals more", "Recalibration: adjust rubric weights when judge-human agreement drops below threshold"], "full_response": "Calibration of the LLM judge means ensuring that its quality scores correspond to real-world recommendation quality as measured by user engagement. A judge that assigns random scores is useless even if it uses sophisticated reasoning.\n\nThe primary calibration method is engagement correlation. I take a large sample of recommendation sets that were served in production, compute the judge''s scores on them, and then check whether higher judge scores correspond to higher engagement (click-through rate, add-to-cart rate). The relationship should be monotonic — average engagement should increase with each score tier. I verified this holds across all 6 rubric types, though the strength of correlation varies (strongest for complementary items, weakest for trending where recency matters more than content quality).\n\nFor judge-human agreement, I run periodic calibration exercises. I sample 200-300 recommendation sets, have them scored by both the judge and by me (acting as the domain expert evaluator). I compute Cohen''s kappa, which adjusts for chance agreement. Our kappa typically ranges from 0.65 to 0.75, which is considered substantial agreement. Perfect agreement isn''t expected — humans and LLMs weight different signals.\n\nThe disagreement analysis revealed systematic patterns. The judge tends to overweight textual similarity between anchor and recommended items (natural for a language model), while human evaluators weight visual appearance and brand reputation more heavily. For example, the judge might rate a generic phone case as equally complementary to an iPhone as an Apple-branded case, but humans strongly prefer the brand match. I incorporated this insight by adding brand coherence as an explicit rubric dimension.\n\nWhen the judge disagrees with human evaluators, I investigate whether it''s the judge or the human who''s wrong. Sometimes the judge catches quality issues that a quick human scan misses — it''s more systematic about checking all items in a list. Other times, the judge misunderstands a cultural or contextual signal that''s obvious to a human.\n\nRecalibration happens when I detect that judge-human agreement has dropped. The most common cause is distribution shift in the recommendation outputs — a new model version produces different types of recommendations that the judge rubric wasn''t calibrated for. The fix is to update the rubric with examples from the new distribution and re-run the human calibration exercise."}'::jsonb WHERE id = '3273067f-b211-42d0-b750-6438e6abdb09';

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "Two-tower retrieval with independent query and item encoders, FAISS ANN index, and cross-encoder reranking for the full retrieval-to-ranking pipeline.", "outline": ["Two-tower architecture: query encoder and item encoder map to shared 128-dim space, trained with InfoNCE loss", "Item embeddings precomputed and stored in FAISS IVF-PQ index for millisecond ANN retrieval over millions of items", "Hard negative mining from previous iteration''s top-K retrievals, curriculum training from random to hard", "Cross-encoder reranking stage processes top-100 candidates with joint query-item attention for +0.192 NDCG"], "full_response": "The two-tower retrieval architecture has a query encoder and an item encoder that map into a shared 128-dimensional embedding space. At training time, both towers process their inputs and we optimize the InfoNCE contrastive loss: for each (query, positive_item) pair, the model learns to maximize the dot product similarity while minimizing similarity with in-batch negatives and mined hard negatives.\n\nThe key design choice of independent encoding is what enables scalable serving. Item embeddings are precomputed in a daily batch job and stored in a FAISS index. We use IVF-PQ (Inverted File with Product Quantization) — IVF partitions the embedding space into clusters for coarse search, and PQ compresses each vector from 128 floats to 32 bytes for memory efficiency. At query time, only the query encoder runs in real-time, producing a vector that FAISS uses to retrieve the top-K nearest items in 5-10ms across millions of items.\n\nThe embedding-to-retrieval pipeline handles the gap between raw embeddings and the ANN index. After computing item embeddings with PyTorch Lightning on V100 GPUs, a Spark job formats them for FAISS, builds the index with appropriate hyperparameters (nprobe=32 for recall-latency balance), and deploys it to the serving layer. Daily delta updates refresh embeddings for items whose attributes changed, with a full rebuild weekly.\n\nNegative sampling strategy was crucial. Random negatives teach coarse discrimination (shoe vs. laptop) but not fine-grained (Nike running shoe vs. Adidas running shoe). I use a curriculum: start training with in-batch random negatives for 2 epochs to learn the coarse structure, then introduce hard negatives mined from the previous training iteration''s top-100 retrievals. The hard negatives are items the model currently confuses with the true positive — these provide the strongest gradient signal for learning fine-grained distinctions.\n\nThe cross-encoder reranking stage sits on top. It takes the top-100 candidates from the two-tower retrieval and jointly encodes (query, item) pairs with cross-attention, producing a relevance score. This gave us +0.192 NDCG improvement over the two-tower scores alone because cross-attention can model fine-grained token-level interactions that independent encoding misses. The tradeoff is latency — 100 cross-encoder forward passes per query adds ~50ms — which is why we use it only as a reranker, not for full-corpus retrieval."}'::jsonb WHERE id = '59bd490c-866c-464f-a391-9c1a6eb83ef1';

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "Cross-encoder reranking achieves +0.192 NDCG by joint query-item attention, measured on 50K queries across 3 markets with careful latency management.", "outline": ["Cross-encoder jointly attends to query and item tokens, capturing fine-grained semantic interactions", "Evaluated on 50K query test set with human relevance judgments across US, CA, MX", "p99 latency managed via two-stage architecture: two-tower retrieves top-100, cross-encoder reranks", "Training: pairwise loss over (query, relevant, irrelevant) triples with hard negatives"], "full_response": "The cross-encoder reranking approach processes each (query, candidate_item) pair through a joint attention model — a BERT-based architecture where query tokens and item tokens attend to each other in every transformer layer. This is fundamentally different from the two-tower model where query and item are encoded independently. The joint attention allows the model to capture fine-grained interactions: it can learn that ''wireless'' in the query should attend strongly to ''bluetooth'' in the item description, or that a price mention in the query should interact with the item''s price attribute.\n\nThe +0.192 NDCG improvement was measured on a curated test set of 50K queries sampled across all three markets (US, CA, MX), with human relevance judgments on a 4-point scale (perfect, excellent, good, irrelevant). The improvement was consistent across markets, though slightly stronger in US (more training data) and slightly weaker in MX (where the model had less Spanish-language training data). We stratified by query type and confirmed gains across head, torso, and tail queries.\n\nLatency was the primary engineering challenge. A cross-encoder processes one (query, item) pair at a time, so scoring 100 candidates means 100 forward passes. We managed this through several optimizations: model distillation from a 12-layer BERT to a 6-layer model with minimal NDCG loss, dynamic batching to process all 100 candidates in parallel on GPU, ONNX export for optimized inference, and careful p99 latency monitoring with automatic fallback to two-tower scores if the reranker exceeds 100ms. The resulting system adds ~50ms p99 to the retrieval pipeline, which was within the latency budget allocated by the product team.\n\nTraining used pairwise loss over (query, relevant_doc, irrelevant_doc) triples. The key insight was that the quality of negatives matters enormously for cross-encoder training. We used the two-tower model''s top retrievals as hard negatives — items that the retrieval model thought were relevant but humans judged as irrelevant. These are exactly the cases where the cross-encoder adds the most value: distinguishing between subtly relevant and subtly irrelevant items that have similar embeddings in the two-tower space."}'::jsonb WHERE id = '30b5a7a9-0e47-485c-9d96-b4aebd391dae';

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "Cold-start item handling via generative retrieval: LLM generates shopping intents from item attributes, covering 100% of catalog without purchase history.", "outline": ["Cold-start problem: 90%+ of catalog has zero purchase data, collaborative filtering impossible", "Solution: generative retrieval pipeline where LLM generates shopping intent queries from item attributes alone", "Item tower fallback: two-tower model generates embeddings from content features for new items", "Exploration mechanism: new items deliberately surfaced in recommendation slots to accumulate engagement data"], "full_response": "Cold-start items are items with no or minimal interaction data — no clicks, no purchases, no engagement signals. In our catalog, over 90% of items in the US had never been purchased, and in Mexico the problem was even more extreme with virtually zero engagement data. Traditional collaborative filtering requires co-purchase patterns to work, so it simply cannot recommend cold-start items.\n\nThe primary solution is the generative retrieval pipeline. For each item, an LLM takes the item''s attributes (title, category, brand, price, description, key features) and generates a set of shopping intent queries — natural language descriptions of what a customer might search for when looking for complementary products. These queries feed into our search infrastructure (Solr for text, FAISS for dense retrieval) to retrieve recommendations. Because the LLM generates queries from content attributes alone, it works for any item regardless of engagement history. A brand-new item added to the catalog today gets recommendations by tomorrow''s batch run.\n\nThe generative approach works because it leverages the LLM''s world knowledge about product relationships. It knows that a customer buying a DSLR camera might want a memory card, a camera bag, and a tripod — without ever having seen a co-purchase pattern for that specific camera model. This is the fundamental advantage over collaborative filtering for cold-start.\n\nFor the two-tower retrieval model, cold-start items get embeddings from the item tower, which processes content features. A new item won''t have behavioral features (click rates, purchase frequency), but the item tower can still produce a meaningful embedding from its title, category, and attributes. The embedding quality is lower than for items with rich behavioral data, but it''s sufficient for candidate generation.\n\nWe also use deliberate exploration. New items are given a boost in certain recommendation slots to accumulate engagement data faster. This is a form of the explore-exploit tradeoff — we sacrifice short-term recommendation quality on a small fraction of slots to gather data that improves long-term recommendations. The boost decays as the item accumulates sufficient engagement signals, typically within 1-2 weeks of launch."}'::jsonb WHERE id = '809628c1-4065-4582-9146-22bb0c9d4c45';

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "ML deployment using Airflow orchestration, Spark for data processing, PyTorch Lightning for GPU inference, with monitoring for stale embeddings and data drift.", "outline": ["Airflow DAGs orchestrate the full pipeline: data extraction, feature computation, model inference, index building", "Spark handles data processing at scale (catalog joins, feature aggregation), PyTorch Lightning on V100s for GPU inference", "Monitoring: embedding distribution drift, stale embedding detection via hash comparison, FAISS index health checks", "Deployment: daily delta updates for changed items, full weekly rebuilds, automatic rollback on quality degradation"], "full_response": "The production ML pipeline is orchestrated by Apache Airflow, with separate DAGs for each major pipeline (similar items, complementary items, generative retrieval, user embeddings). Each DAG follows a common pattern: data extraction from our data lake, feature computation in Spark, model inference on GPU, post-processing and validation, and index deployment.\n\nSpark handles all the data-heavy operations: joining catalog attributes, aggregating user behavior signals, computing features like category co-occurrence statistics, and preparing batches for GPU inference. PyTorch Lightning runs the actual model inference on V100 GPUs. I separated these stages deliberately — Spark tasks run on CPU workers without GPU allocation, and only the inference tasks request GPU resources. This saves significant infrastructure cost compared to running everything on GPU-enabled workers.\n\nFor the generative retrieval pipeline specifically, the Airflow DAG runs daily with delta updates. It identifies items whose attributes changed since the last run (using hash comparison), generates new queries via the RL-trained model through vLLM, retrieves recommendations via FAISS, and updates the serving index. A full rebuild runs weekly to catch any items that might have been missed by delta logic.\n\nMonitoring operates at multiple levels. First, I track embedding distribution statistics — mean cosine similarity between queries and their top retrievals, embedding norm distributions, and cluster occupancy in the FAISS IVF index. A shift in these distributions signals that the input data or model is drifting. Second, stale embedding detection: I compare the hash of each item''s current attributes against the hash used to generate its embedding. Items where the hash differs have stale embeddings that need regeneration — this was the exact bug pattern from the Earn Trust story, and I built explicit monitoring for it after that experience. Third, FAISS index health checks: index size, query latency percentiles, and recall measured against a small set of known-good (query, relevant_items) pairs.\n\nAutomatic rollback triggers on two conditions: if the embedding drift metric exceeds 2 standard deviations from the 30-day rolling mean, or if the retrieval recall on the canary query set drops below a threshold. The rollback reverts to the previous day''s index while an alert fires for investigation."}'::jsonb WHERE id = '35e81ce4-5e0b-464d-9d75-00bd4e9af6ef';

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "Diagnosed similar items pipeline failure: image embeddings added complexity without quality benefit, proven by LLM-judge evaluation rubric.", "outline": ["Similar items pipeline partially working in Mexico, failing in US and Canada due to scaling issues", "Root cause investigation: A100 over-provisioning, CPU-bound inference, unevaluated image embedding component", "Built LLM-judge evaluation rubric for similar items — first systematic quality metric for this pipeline", "Rubric showed image embeddings had zero measurable quality impact — removed them, simplified architecture"], "full_response": "The similar items pipeline had been built as a proof of concept and launched successfully in Mexico, but it was failing when the team tried to scale it to the US and Canadian markets. The symptoms were: pipeline jobs timing out, inconsistent embedding quality across markets, and no clear metric to evaluate whether the recommendations were actually good.\n\nI started by reviewing the pipeline architecture. Three issues became apparent. First, it was provisioned on A100 GPUs for a text encoder that didn''t need that much compute — the A100s were expensive and hard to get allocated, creating a bottleneck. Second, the actual embedding inference was running on Spark CPU workers instead of GPU, which meant the expensive GPUs were allocated but underutilized while the CPU workers were overwhelmed. Third, image embeddings had been added as a secondary filtering signal — items were first retrieved by text similarity, then reranked by image similarity — but this component had never been evaluated for impact.\n\nThe image embedding question was the most consequential. The team had a reasonable intuition that visual similarity matters for ''similar items,'' but intuition isn''t evidence. I wrote an LLM-judge evaluation rubric specifically for similar items — scoring relevance, visual coherence, category appropriateness, and brand compatibility. No such metric existed before; the team had been evaluating by manual spot-checking.\n\nI ran the rubric on three configurations: text-only, image-only, and text+image. The result was decisive — text+image scored identically to text-only on the rubric. The image embeddings were adding computational complexity, infrastructure cost, and failure modes (the image model was a separate dependency) with zero measurable quality benefit. I removed the image component entirely and replaced it with a lighter-weight category filter.\n\nI then rewrote the embedding generation in PyTorch Lightning with native multi-GPU support on V100s (cheaper and easier to provision than A100s), separating data processing from GPU inference. The rewritten pipeline went from partially working in one market to running reliably across all three with approximately 100x throughput improvement."}'::jsonb WHERE id = '4af4e754-bd4f-4637-ba9d-07d747ccd8d3';

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "Three-layer content safety architecture with rule-based filters, ML classifier, and LLM judge, with locale-specific thresholds for US, CA, and MX.", "outline": ["Layer 1: Rule-based blocklist and regex patterns for known unsafe content (fast, high precision)", "Layer 2: ML classifier trained on human-labeled data for nuanced content categorization", "Layer 3: LLM judge with safety rubric for edge cases and novel content types", "Locale-specific thresholds: stricter for children''s categories, adjusted for cultural norms across US/CA/MX"], "full_response": "The content safety architecture uses three layers, each trading off speed, cost, and judgment quality.\n\nLayer 1 is rule-based: blocklists of known unsafe terms, regex patterns for common unsafe content patterns (phone numbers, URLs in product descriptions, known scam phrases), and hard category blocks (certain product categories have blanket restrictions in certain markets). This layer processes in microseconds, catches the obvious cases, and has near-perfect precision. But it has zero ability to handle novel unsafe content or nuanced cases.\n\nLayer 2 is an ML classifier trained on human-labeled data. The training set is a corpus of product content labeled as safe, unsafe-flagged, or borderline by a human review team. The model learns to detect patterns that go beyond keyword matching — tone, context, combinations of individually safe words that become unsafe together. It outputs a probability score that feeds into the threshold logic.\n\nLayer 3 is an LLM judge with a safety-specific rubric. This is reserved for content that falls in the uncertain zone of Layer 2 (probability between the auto-pass and auto-block thresholds). The LLM judge evaluates the content against a structured rubric covering: harmful claims, misleading health/safety information, inappropriate imagery descriptions, regulatory compliance (claims that require FDA approval, etc.), and cultural sensitivity. It provides a scored judgment with reasoning.\n\nLocale-specific thresholds are essential because safety standards differ across markets. Mexico has different regulatory frameworks than the US for health claims, supplement descriptions, and product warnings. Children''s product categories have globally stricter thresholds — we apply the most conservative threshold across all markets. The threshold configuration is a mapping from (market, category_type) to (auto_pass_threshold, auto_block_threshold, review_routing), maintained as a configuration file that the policy team can update without model retraining.\n\nThe key insight is that the three layers are complementary, not redundant. Rules catch the easy cases cheaply, the ML classifier handles the bulk volume with moderate cost, and the LLM judge handles the long tail of novel cases that require reasoning. This layered approach keeps the LLM cost manageable — only 2-3% of content reaches Layer 3."}'::jsonb WHERE id = 'b85c3821-3e83-4962-8cb1-87ede90628e1';

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "Generative retrieval uses LLM reasoning about shopping intent vs collaborative filtering''s reliance on co-purchase patterns, solving the cold-start problem.", "outline": ["Collaborative filtering learns from co-purchase patterns: ''users who bought X also bought Y''", "Generative retrieval generates the reasoning: LLM infers what a customer might want based on item attributes", "Key advantage: works on items with zero purchase history (90%+ of catalog)", "Text queries as intermediary enable reuse of existing search infrastructure (Solr, FAISS)"], "full_response": "Traditional collaborative filtering recommends items based on observed co-purchase or co-interaction patterns. The fundamental operation is: find items that frequently co-occur with the anchor item in user sessions or purchase baskets, then rank by co-occurrence strength. Matrix factorization learns latent factors that capture these patterns. The approach works well when you have dense interaction data — popular items in mature markets.\n\nThe generative retrieval pipeline operates on a completely different principle. Instead of learning from behavioral patterns, it generates the reasoning about what a customer might want. For a given anchor item, the LLM takes the item''s attributes and generates shopping intent queries: ''What would a customer who just bought a mechanical gaming keyboard also want? A wrist rest for ergonomic typing during long gaming sessions. A custom keycap set to personalize their keyboard. A large desk mat to accommodate both keyboard and mouse.''\n\nThese generated queries then feed into existing search infrastructure — text queries go to Solr for keyword matching, and query embeddings go to FAISS for dense retrieval. The retrieved items become the recommendations.\n\nThe fundamental difference is the source of knowledge. Collaborative filtering''s knowledge is in the data — it can only recommend items that have co-occurred with similar items in the past. Generative retrieval''s knowledge is in the LLM — it understands product relationships through world knowledge learned during pretraining. A gaming keyboard and a wrist rest are complementary because the LLM understands ergonomics and gaming setups, not because it observed co-purchases.\n\nThis is why generative retrieval solves cold-start. A brand-new item with zero purchase history has no co-occurrence signals, so collaborative filtering produces nothing. But the LLM can still generate meaningful intent queries from the item''s title, category, and description. At Walmart, where 90%+ of catalog items had never been purchased, this was the difference between having recommendations for the full catalog versus recommendations only for the popular head.\n\nThe text intermediary also provides interpretability — you can inspect the generated queries to understand why the model recommended what it did, unlike opaque embedding-space approaches. And the queries are modular — they can be reused for other purposes like search suggestion and query understanding."}'::jsonb WHERE id = 'fa62dfc6-7b0f-4604-b5b6-e9ecd597ff2f';

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "Natural language queries as intermediary leverage LLM world knowledge for genuine diversity, provide interpretability, and produce modular reusable components.", "outline": ["LLM world knowledge: understands that gaming chair + gaming mouse are both complements for gaming keyboard", "Interpretability: generated queries are human-readable, unlike opaque embedding probes", "Modularity: query generation and retrieval models reusable separately across projects", "Offline batch processing eliminates the latency objection — not competing with real-time serving"], "full_response": "The decision to generate natural language queries as an intermediary rather than staying in embedding space was controversial. The alternative architecture was a pure embedding approach: item embeddings feed into a ComiRec retrieval model with multiple embedding probes for diversity, followed by dense retrieval and reranking. It was faster and arguably more elegant. But the LLM-based approach won on three dimensions.\n\nFirst, diversity through world knowledge. For complementary recommendations, you need genuine diversity — not just items that are similar to each other, but items that serve different aspects of a common use case. A gaming chair and a gaming mouse are both excellent complements for a gaming keyboard, but they have very different embeddings in any standard embedding space. A one-shot dense retrieval model with embedding probes produces a cluster of similar items (other keyboards, keyboard accessories) because that''s what proximity in embedding space means. The LLM understands the concept of a ''gaming setup'' and generates queries that explore different facets of that intent — seating, peripherals, desk organization, lighting. This world knowledge doesn''t exist in the training data of a standard embedding model.\n\nSecond, interpretability. When a recommendation looks wrong, you can inspect the generated queries to understand why. ''Why did we recommend a fish tank for a desk lamp?'' becomes easy to diagnose when you can see the generated query was ''desk accessories for home office ambiance.'' With opaque embedding probes, debugging requires analyzing high-dimensional vectors, which is much harder. In practice, interpretability saved us hours of debugging time and gave PMs confidence in the system because they could understand its reasoning.\n\nThird, modularity. The query generation model and the retrieval model are separate components that can be improved and reused independently. The query generation model was reused to generate training data for supervised fine-tuning of other models. The label data I generated (pairwise relevance judgments between generated queries and retrieved items) was used by other teams for hard negatives in similar items retrieval. A monolithic embedding-based system doesn''t decompose as cleanly.\n\nThe speed objection — that LLM generation is slow — doesn''t apply because this is an offline batch signal. We generate queries for 3M anchor items in a daily batch job, not at query time. The latency constraint is ''complete within the nightly batch window,'' not ''respond in 100ms.''"}'::jsonb WHERE id = '3b3aadf0-6435-4777-8d50-3b0746efbd88';

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "Paper evaluation process: read, implement from scratch, benchmark against existing systems with full hyperparameter sweeps. 10+ architectures compared, ComiRec-SA won.", "outline": ["Step 1: Read paper critically — does the method address a real gap in our system?", "Step 2: Implement from scratch in our stack (PyTorch Lightning, Spark) — no research-only frameworks", "Step 3: Benchmark against existing production approach with identical data and hyperparameter sweeps", "Step 4: If it wins, productionize. If it loses, extract reusable components (ComiRec-SA won for user-item retrieval)"], "full_response": "My process for evaluating research papers has four steps, and the most important discipline is that step 2 (implementation) must happen before you form a strong opinion.\n\nStep 1: Critical reading. I ask three questions. Does this method address a real gap in our current system — not a theoretical limitation, but something that''s actually hurting metrics or user experience? Is the evaluation setup in the paper reasonable, or is it cherry-picked to make the method look good? And does the method make assumptions that hold in our production setting (data scale, feature types, latency constraints)? Most papers fail step 1 — they solve problems we don''t have, or they evaluate on toy datasets that don''t represent production conditions.\n\nStep 2: Implementation from scratch. I implement the method in our production stack — PyTorch Lightning for the model, Spark for data processing, our actual training data and feature pipeline. I explicitly avoid using the authors'' reference code (if available) because: (a) it''s usually written for a different framework and data format, requiring more adaptation work than a fresh implementation, (b) implementing from scratch forces me to deeply understand every design choice, and (c) I need the implementation to be production-ready from day one, not a research prototype that needs rewriting later.\n\nStep 3: Rigorous benchmarking. Same data, same evaluation methodology, same compute budget, full hyperparameter sweep for both the new method and the existing production approach. This is where most ''paper beating production'' claims fall apart — the paper method was tuned extensively by its authors, while the production baseline hasn''t been tuned in months. Fair comparison requires tuning both. I compared 10+ architectures this way: DeepRetrieval (RL-based query generation), ComiRec-DR (dynamic routing), ComiRec-SA (self-attentive), SASRec (self-attention sequential), Choppy (list truncation), and several baselines.\n\nStep 4: Decision. ComiRec-SA won the architecture comparison for user-item retrieval — it provided strong retrieval quality for engaged items with good diversity. The RL-trained query generation model won for item-to-item generative retrieval. Methods that lost still provided value — I extracted reusable components. The billions of cached pairwise predictions from the RL reward computation became shared training data for supervised fine-tuning across the team."}'::jsonb WHERE id = '96c1f848-a552-468d-b547-fe4f5374aabf';
